\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chiral symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider the Lagrangian of two flavors massless fermions, and the results
 will be directly applicable to massless QCD.
 The Lagrangian is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}=i\bar{\psi_{j}}\gamma_{\mu}\partial^{\mu}\psi_{j}\label{eq:L_massless}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the index 
\emph on
j 
\emph default
presents the two different flavors (
\emph on
u
\emph default
, 
\emph on
d
\emph default
).
 Consider two transformation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
vector transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{V}$
\end_inset

 :
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda_{V}:\;\psi\rightarrow e^{-i\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}\vec{\Theta}}\psi\simeq(1-i\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}\vec{\Theta})\psi
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and its conjugate form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda_{V}:\;\bar{\psi}\rightarrow e^{+i\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}\vec{\Theta}}\bar{\psi}\simeq(1+i\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}\vec{\Theta})\bar{\psi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is the Pauli-spin-matrices and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Theta}$
\end_inset

 are the rotation angle.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is the Dirac iso-spinor for fermions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=(\psi_{u},\psi_{d})$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly the Lagrangian is invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{V}$
\end_inset

 and the associated conserved current is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\mu}^{a}=\bar{\psi}\gamma_{\mu}\frac{\tau^{a}}{2}\psi
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
axial transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{A}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Lambda_{A}:\;\psi & \rightarrow e^{-i\gamma_{5}\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}\vec{\Theta}}\psi\simeq(1-i\gamma_{5}\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}\vec{\Theta})\psi\\
\bar{\psi} & \rightarrow e^{-i\gamma_{5}\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}\vec{\Theta}}\bar{\psi}\simeq(1-i\gamma_{5}\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}\vec{\Theta})\bar{\psi}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The Lagrangian transforms as following :
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i\bar{\psi}\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi\rightarrow i\bar{\psi}\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi-i\vec{\Theta}(\bar{\psi}i\partial_{\mu}\gamma^{\mu}\gamma_{5}\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}\psi+\bar{\psi}\gamma_{5}\frac{\vec{\tau}}{2}i\partial_{\mu}\gamma^{\mu}\psi)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{5}$
\end_inset

 anti-commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\mu}$
\end_inset

, the last term vanishes.
 Therefore the Lagrangian is also invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{A}$
\end_inset

 with the conserved 'axial-vector' current: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{\mu}^{a}=\bar{\psi}\gamma_{\mu}\gamma_{5}\frac{\tau^{a}}{2}\psi
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, the Lagrangian of massless QCD is invariant under the vector and axial
 transformations.
 This symmetry is called 
\emph on
chiral symmetry
\emph default
.
 If we introduce a mass term in the Lagrangian.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\mathcal{L}=-m(\bar{\psi}\psi)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It can easily prove the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under the vector transformations, but the axial transformations
 symmetry is broken.
 In case of QCD, the mass of the light quarks are very small (about 5~10
 MeV) comparing to the QCD energy scale which is about 200 MeV.
 Therefore, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{A}$
\end_inset

 should be an approximate symmetry.
 And the slight symmetry breaking due to the quark masses is called Partial
 Conserved Axial Current hypothesis (PCAC).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spontaneous breaking of chiral symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conservation of chiral symmetry leads to a direct deduction that the
 chiral partner which can be rotated into each other by the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{A}$
\end_inset

 should have the same masses, since they should have the same Eigenvalues.
 However, in the real world, this is clearly not true, since the chiral
 partner 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 have quite difference masses (
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\rho}=770$
\end_inset

 MeV and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{a_{1}}=1260$
\end_inset

 MeV).
 This can not be explained by the slight symmetry breaking due to the finite
 current quark masses, because this should lead to a mass difference much
 smaller than the particle mass, however, the mass difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 is of the same order as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 mass.
 On the other hand, let us consider the weak decay of pion which is controlled
 by the matrix element of the axial current between vacuum and pion 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle 0|A_{\mu}^{a}(x)|\pi^{b}(q)\right\rangle =-if_{\pi}q_{\mu}\delta^{ab}e^{-iq\cdot x}\label{eq:pi_wd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 is a constant ~ 93 MeV determined from experiment.
 If we take the divergence of eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pi_wd"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle 0|\partial^{\mu}A_{\mu}^{a}(x)|\pi^{b}(q)\right\rangle =-if_{\pi}q_{\mu}q^{\mu}\delta^{ab}e^{-iq\cdot x}=-f_{\pi}m_{\pi}^{2}\delta^{ab}e^{-iq\cdot x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Comparing to the hadronic scales, the pion mass is vanishing, thus the axial
 current is approximately conserved.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the contradiction discussed above, the spontaneous breakdown of
 chiral symmetry was introduced.
 The breaking of symmetry has two conditions: explicit breaking, which is
 due to the explicit asymmetry in the Lagrangian, i.e.
 the finite mass of quarks in QCD; spontaneous breaking, which means the
 symmetry is not realized in the ground state.
 We considering effective potentials shown in fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sbsc"

\end_inset

.
 Panel (a) shows a potential with ground state just in the middle.
 The ground state plus potential are invariant under rotations.
 In panel (b), any points in the valley can be the ground state.
 If we chosen as one direction as the ground state, the axial rotation symmetry
 is obviously spontaneously broken, since the Lagrangian is invariant but
 the vacuum is not.
 According to the Goldstone theorem (cite), the spontaneous breaking of
 chiral symmetry of QCD leads to the existence of eight massless Goldstone
 bosons (
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{\pm}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\pm}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{K^{0}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 ), which correspond the invariant of the field under axial-vector rotations.
 And the massive particles correspond the excitations alone the radial direction.
 The assumption of spontaneously broken axial-vector symmetry also explains
 the mass difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 meson.
 Theory calculations predict that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{a_{1}}=\sqrt{2}m_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.18.507"

\end_inset

 which is in good agreement with the measured masses.
\end_layout

